<subSubSection pageId="30" pageNumber="31" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="30.[151,1437,972,1287]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,274,972,998]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Vertex with an almost perpendicular, laterally compressed, pointed process with obtuse tip (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="32.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[178,1409,181,1913]" captionTargetId="figure-21@32.[178,1409,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="32" captionText="FIGURE 18. Apolinaria hygracantha (Karsch, 1896). A. Male holotype in lateral view. B–C. Head and pronotum in lateral and dorsal view. D. Ovipositor in lateral view. E–F. Male cerci in lateral and latero-dorsal view (after Rehn, 1950)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876257" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876257/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Figs. 18AB</figureCitation>
). Pronotal disc with laterally expanded metazone (
<figureCitation box="[735,837,1008,1035]" captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="32.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[178,1409,181,1913]" captionTargetId="figure-21@32.[178,1409,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="32" captionText="FIGURE 18. Apolinaria hygracantha (Karsch, 1896). A. Male holotype in lateral view. B–C. Head and pronotum in lateral and dorsal view. D. Ovipositor in lateral view. E–F. Male cerci in lateral and latero-dorsal view (after Rehn, 1950)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876257" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876257/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Fig. 18C</figureCitation>
). Hind femora and tibiae with elongate, curved spines (
<figureCitation box="[159,265,1044,1071]" captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="32.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[178,1409,181,1913]" captionTargetId="figure-21@32.[178,1409,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="32" captionText="FIGURE 18. Apolinaria hygracantha (Karsch, 1896). A. Male holotype in lateral view. B–C. Head and pronotum in lateral and dorsal view. D. Ovipositor in lateral view. E–F. Male cerci in lateral and latero-dorsal view (after Rehn, 1950)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876257" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876257/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Fig. 18A</figureCitation>
). All genicular lobes developed in the shape of an elongated spine. Tegmina relatively short and not extending beyond tips of extended hind femora, maximum width almost equal to 2/5 of the length (
<figureCitation box="[1253,1359,1080,1107]" captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="32.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[178,1409,181,1913]" captionTargetId="figure-21@32.[178,1409,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="32" captionText="FIGURE 18. Apolinaria hygracantha (Karsch, 1896). A. Male holotype in lateral view. B–C. Head and pronotum in lateral and dorsal view. D. Ovipositor in lateral view. E–F. Male cerci in lateral and latero-dorsal view (after Rehn, 1950)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876257" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876257/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Fig. 18A</figureCitation>
). Male cerci short, robust, and with hairs on basal surface. Both branches curved perpendicularly upward, then narrowing toward the tip (
<figureCitation box="[322,464,1152,1179]" captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="32.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[178,1409,181,1913]" captionTargetId="figure-21@32.[178,1409,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="32" captionText="FIGURE 18. Apolinaria hygracantha (Karsch, 1896). A. Male holotype in lateral view. B–C. Head and pronotum in lateral and dorsal view. D. Ovipositor in lateral view. E–F. Male cerci in lateral and latero-dorsal view (after Rehn, 1950)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876257" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876257/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Figs. 18E–F</figureCitation>
). Ovipositor curved with rounded and delicately toothed tip. Female cerci thin and half as long as ovipositor (
<figureCitation box="[397,502,1188,1215]" captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="32.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[178,1409,181,1913]" captionTargetId="figure-21@32.[178,1409,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="32" captionText="FIGURE 18. Apolinaria hygracantha (Karsch, 1896). A. Male holotype in lateral view. B–C. Head and pronotum in lateral and dorsal view. D. Ovipositor in lateral view. E–F. Male cerci in lateral and latero-dorsal view (after Rehn, 1950)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876257" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876257/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Fig. 18D</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
